title: 54,56Fe and 58,60Ni(gamma,n), (gamma,p), (gamma,np), and (gamma,2n) cross sections evaluation using the model of GDR (Giant Dipole Resonance) decay channel competition phenomenological description.

x4freetext: 54,56Fe and 58,60Ni(gamma,n), (gamma,p), (gamma,np),
and (gamma,2n) cross sections evaluation using the
model of GDR (Giant Dipole Resonance) decay channel
competition phenomenological description.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Moscow State Univ.Inst.of Nucl.Phys.Reports, No.2000-6/610 (2000)

x4freetext: The short model description is the following:
- the channel cross section sig-I(E) is proposed to
be  proportional  to  dipole   state   excitation
probability  W-exc(E)  and the appropriate partial
width width-I(E) sig-I(E) = W-exc(E) x width-I(E);
- for  nuclei  with  N  =  Z the single Breit-Wigner
curve description   is    proposed    for    total
photoabsorption cross section with the maximum at
MeV;
- for nuclei with  different  N  and  Z  the  double
Breit-Wigner  curves  description  is proposed for
well known components  of  GDR  isospin  splitting
- sig for one component and the sum sig> + sig<  for
two component  total photoabsorption cross section
is equal to 60nz/a;
- Breit-Wigner  curve  width  estimation is based on
the best     description      of      experimental
photoabsorption cross section;
- the proton emission reduction is  described  using
the Coulomb  barrier  factor C(E) = exp ((-H-C/B x
a**(-1/3)(e - e-p), where H-C is the barrier high,
B is  the  constant  obtained  from the (gamma,p)
and (gamma,xn) reaction experimental cross sections
ratio best description;
- two-neutron  emission   was   described   as   the
sequential process  of  the  (A-1,Z)  and  (A-2,Z)
nuclei states occupation.
The 54,56Fe, 58,60Ni photonuclear reactions (gamma,n),
(gamma,p),  (gamma,np),  (gamma,2n)  cross  sections
have  been evaluated using the simple  semiempirical
model  of giant dipole resonance  decay channel
competition.
The model    was   based   on   the   phenomenologic
description  of  the  main  giant  dipole  resonance
channel  competition and used the parametrization of
the main giant dipole resonance excitation and decay
mechanisms.
The evaluated  data  are  compared   with   available
experimental data.
By V.V.Varlamov.
